WEBVTT

00:01.830 --> 00:03.760
- We got 39 families
looking for justice.

00:03.960 --> 00:07.680
- But when I get this case file,
it's got to be legit.

00:07.700 --> 00:08.740
- Hi, Tamra.

00:08.890 --> 00:09.970
Do you remember anything
about him?

00:09.990 --> 00:13.270
- He had a silver skull ring.

00:13.290 --> 00:15.010
- Dylan Oates, 22.

00:15.030 --> 00:16.880
- You know,
I work with a detective.

00:16.900 --> 00:19.010
You killed his daughter
in that fire.

00:19.030 --> 00:22.250
- Heard you had a suspect.
- He, uh, confessed.

00:22.270 --> 00:23.920
- To who?
- Me.

00:23.940 --> 00:26.740
- What did he say exactly?
- Do you want the case or not?

00:29.010 --> 00:30.990
[indistinct chatter]

00:31.010 --> 00:32.860
[camera shutters clicking]

00:32.880 --> 00:33.860
- What can you tell us
about him?

00:33.880 --> 00:36.600
- His name is Dylan Oates.
He's 22 years old.

00:36.620 --> 00:38.260
- We heard he confessed.
- No comment.

00:38.280 --> 00:39.770
- Why'd he do it, Mr. Stone?

00:39.790 --> 00:40.970
- Pyromaniacs don't need
a reason.

00:40.990 --> 00:42.600
- The fact is,
Mr. Oates has asserted

00:42.620 --> 00:43.800
his Fifth Amendment rights.

00:43.820 --> 00:45.040
I haven't spoken to him
as of yet.

00:45.060 --> 00:46.810
- But he's the guy?

00:46.830 --> 00:48.640
- Yes, he is.

00:48.660 --> 00:50.580
- Does he have an attorney?
- Is he from Chicago?

00:50.600 --> 00:52.880
- Mr. Stone,
does he have a record?

00:52.900 --> 00:57.320
[indistinct chatter]

00:57.340 --> 01:00.020
[camera shutters clicking]

01:00.040 --> 01:03.060
[pensive music]

01:03.080 --> 01:06.790
♪

01:06.810 --> 01:08.630
- We don't usually
get to see you

01:08.650 --> 01:10.700
at a bond hearing, Mr. Stone.

01:10.720 --> 01:15.800
But this isn't
your garden-variety homicide.

01:15.820 --> 01:17.700
Where's your attorney, son?

01:17.720 --> 01:18.640
- I don't have one.

01:18.660 --> 01:20.640
Excuse me, Judge,
but this is just about

01:20.660 --> 01:21.910
whether or not
I get bail, right?

01:21.930 --> 01:23.140
- That is correct.

01:23.160 --> 01:25.010
- Then it doesn't really matter,
does it?

01:25.030 --> 01:27.580
I waive counsel.
- Hang him!

01:27.600 --> 01:29.350
- Burn him!
- You killed my boy!

01:29.370 --> 01:32.610
[indistinct shouting]

01:34.670 --> 01:35.820
[gavel bangs]

01:35.840 --> 01:37.790
- No bail it is.

01:37.810 --> 01:38.730
Next case.

01:38.750 --> 01:41.880
- Get him out of here!
- See you in hell!

01:55.860 --> 01:57.380
- You don't want to know
how many cases

01:57.460 --> 01:59.780
with confessions
I've seen crash and burn.

01:59.800 --> 02:01.650
- You may want to add this
to the pile.

02:01.670 --> 02:02.950
Voight says he confessed.

02:02.970 --> 02:04.320
- But you have your doubts.

02:04.340 --> 02:06.250
- I haven't heard
from Dawson yet,

02:06.270 --> 02:07.790
but Olinsky's kid died
in the fire.

02:07.810 --> 02:10.660
- Hmm. Good morning.
- But a girl did ID the suspect.

02:10.680 --> 02:13.030
- She saw him set the fire?
- Yes.

02:13.050 --> 02:14.860
- And she picked him
out of a lineup?

02:14.880 --> 02:16.900
- She's having trouble
with her vision.

02:16.920 --> 02:20.300
- But she described
his ring and his coat.

02:20.320 --> 02:22.240
He was wearing both
when he was arrested.

02:22.260 --> 02:24.970
- Why?
- Because he's a monster.

02:24.990 --> 02:26.910
- Someone kills 39 kids

02:26.930 --> 02:28.710
and injures
God knows how many more...

02:28.730 --> 02:30.310
You're damn right
he's a monster.

02:30.330 --> 02:32.350
The problem is
juries can't accept it.

02:32.370 --> 02:33.980
It's out of their comfort zone.

02:34.000 --> 02:36.350
But you give them
a big, fat, juicy "why,"

02:36.370 --> 02:38.790
and they'll crawl into
their beds, close their eyes,

02:38.810 --> 02:41.390
and drift off,
thinking they're actually safe.

02:41.410 --> 02:43.820
- I'll put Dawson and Nagel
on it.

02:43.840 --> 02:46.760
- Oh, and, Peter...

02:46.780 --> 02:50.760
Enormous tragedies
make career cases.

02:50.780 --> 02:53.970
You win this one,
it could make your career.

02:53.990 --> 02:58.660
But you lose,
it could destroy mine.

03:03.960 --> 03:05.000
- Hey.

03:12.310 --> 03:14.990
- Hey, man.
I'm so sorry.

03:15.010 --> 03:17.720
- Yeah. Yeah.

03:17.740 --> 03:20.760
- Hey...

03:20.780 --> 03:23.730
I loved Lexi.
We all did.

03:23.750 --> 03:26.370
- Domestic monitors.
Can you believe this crap?

03:26.390 --> 03:29.060
Like I'm gonna hurt my own kid.

03:32.030 --> 03:34.430
I'm sorry for your loss, Al.

03:36.930 --> 03:39.410
- [softly] Thanks.

03:39.430 --> 03:41.840
Walk with me for a second.

03:48.470 --> 03:52.030
You know, the thing is,
sometimes guys in your position

03:52.050 --> 03:54.290
might get hit
by a bout of ethics,

03:54.310 --> 03:57.130
and then there's some
pain-in-the-ass defense attorney

03:57.150 --> 03:59.450
crying coercion.

04:03.320 --> 04:05.360
Okay, good.

04:10.060 --> 04:11.930
- Did he confess, Al?

04:13.830 --> 04:17.779
- That son of a bitch...

04:17.800 --> 04:20.120
he killed Lexi.

04:20.140 --> 04:23.120
[melancholy music]

04:23.140 --> 04:30.350
♪

04:32.920 --> 04:34.350
- Jesus.

04:36.190 --> 04:39.440
- How bad am I, complaining
about my kid issues?

04:39.460 --> 04:40.310
I honestly don't know

04:40.330 --> 04:42.480
how he's gonna make it
through the day.

04:42.500 --> 04:45.810
- All I know is I couldn't.

04:45.830 --> 04:48.150
- So was that the sound
of the vice squeezing?

04:48.170 --> 04:51.950
- You want to ask me something,
go ahead.

04:51.970 --> 04:54.020
- On a good day,
a confession from your old crew

04:54.040 --> 04:55.190
smells a little hinky.

04:55.210 --> 04:56.860
With Olinsky's kid a victim...

04:56.880 --> 04:59.890
- I don't know, okay?

04:59.910 --> 05:02.060
I wasn't there,
so I didn't hear anything.

05:02.080 --> 05:04.160
- Hey, I'm a team player,
is all.

05:04.180 --> 05:07.520
I'd just like to know which team
I'm on before the game starts.

05:12.560 --> 05:14.070
[indistinct shouting]
- We need you to move back.

05:14.090 --> 05:15.570
- Uh-uh, back up.

05:15.590 --> 05:17.510
No comment.

05:17.530 --> 05:19.200
Come on.
- You hear her? Back up.

05:20.400 --> 05:22.980
- This is all a shock.
I'm sorry.

05:23.000 --> 05:24.980
James!

05:25.000 --> 05:28.020
I just can't get those
poor children out of my head.

05:28.040 --> 05:29.420
What you must think of us...

05:29.440 --> 05:32.160
Dylan couldn't have done this.

05:32.180 --> 05:35.900
- Why do you say that?
- We're good people.

05:35.920 --> 05:37.930
James, these people
are investigators

05:37.950 --> 05:40.470
from the State's Attorney's
office.

05:40.490 --> 05:43.140
- You can't talk to us.
We have rights.

05:43.160 --> 05:44.000
- Actually, you don't

05:44.020 --> 05:45.870
until someone accuses you
of something.

05:45.890 --> 05:47.860
- Yeah, we'll see about that.

05:49.430 --> 05:52.150
- Did Dylan go to the party
with anyone?

05:52.170 --> 05:55.180
- I don't really know
who his friends are.

05:55.200 --> 05:57.080
I doubt he would even
go to a rave.

05:57.100 --> 05:59.020
- When are these pricks
gonna leave us alone?

05:59.040 --> 06:01.440
- Unfortunately,
they have rights.

06:05.580 --> 06:06.560
- Why did you say

06:06.580 --> 06:09.560
that Dylan wouldn't go
to a rave, Mrs. Oates?

06:09.580 --> 06:11.970
- He kept to himself, mostly.

06:11.990 --> 06:14.130
His head was always
in his computer.

06:14.150 --> 06:16.000
Eight hours a day
wasn't enough for him.

06:16.020 --> 06:17.070
- He was a programmer?

06:17.090 --> 06:20.860
- Data processing...
Whatever that is.

06:32.240 --> 06:34.490
[knock at door]

06:34.510 --> 06:35.960
- Hey.

06:35.980 --> 06:38.290
What'd you find?

06:38.310 --> 06:41.560
- He's snooty.
He's weird. He's shy.

06:41.580 --> 06:42.900
He'd "never go dancing."

06:42.920 --> 06:44.930
Nobody seems to know
a lot about him.

06:44.950 --> 06:47.470
But he spends
a lot of time online.

06:47.490 --> 06:50.120
- Unfortunately, none of that
is an element of murder.

06:51.930 --> 06:53.060
- Right.

06:58.230 --> 06:59.680
You don't have kids, do you?

06:59.700 --> 07:02.220
- No.

07:02.240 --> 07:06.220
- I remember when I could hold
Diego in the palm of my hand.

07:06.240 --> 07:08.960
I'd look at him and think,

07:08.980 --> 07:10.920
"There's a surgeon,

07:10.940 --> 07:12.980
a one guard for the Bulls."

07:15.610 --> 07:18.560
I want to grab Olinsky...

07:18.580 --> 07:22.000
and tell him it's gonna be okay,
but it's not.

07:22.020 --> 07:24.200
It never will be.

07:24.220 --> 07:27.170
[sighs]

07:27.190 --> 07:29.680
The confession...

07:29.700 --> 07:32.110
I didn't actually hear it.

07:32.130 --> 07:34.980
[dramatic music]

07:35.000 --> 07:36.650
- Who did?

07:36.670 --> 07:38.350
- Voight and Olinsky.

07:38.370 --> 07:41.320
- [scoffs]

07:41.340 --> 07:45.190
You know, truth be told,

07:45.210 --> 07:47.530
I was waiting
for you to come to me.

07:47.550 --> 07:50.030
I just didn't expect
it would take you 24 hours.

07:50.050 --> 07:52.100
- Olinsky's daughter died
in that fire.

07:52.120 --> 07:53.670
I figured maybe he's entitled...

07:53.690 --> 07:55.670
- To what? Revenge?
- Yeah.

07:55.690 --> 07:58.300
- One lie like this
can destroy my entire case.

07:58.320 --> 08:01.140
- Your case?
It's his kid.

08:01.160 --> 08:02.230
- Fine.

08:04.130 --> 08:06.710
- Albert Forest made a motion
to suppress the confession.

08:06.730 --> 08:09.750
♪

08:09.770 --> 08:12.290
- Albert Forest is
representing Dylan?

08:12.310 --> 08:14.370
- Today's just brimming
with good news.

08:18.640 --> 08:20.030
- Excuse me.

08:20.050 --> 08:26.370
♪

08:26.390 --> 08:29.040
[siren wailing]

08:29.060 --> 08:30.700
- Fancy seeing you here.

08:30.720 --> 08:33.210
- I knew a guy...

08:33.230 --> 08:36.640
He ate a hot dog a day,
lived to be 98.

08:36.659 --> 08:38.240
- I doubt it was the hot dogs.

08:38.260 --> 08:42.049
- He swears it was.
I trust him.

08:42.070 --> 08:44.320
You should trust me.

08:44.340 --> 08:46.720
- We'll see.

08:46.740 --> 08:49.380
- Peter, let me do this.

08:52.680 --> 08:54.690
I got a right to take the stand,

08:54.710 --> 08:57.620
tell my story, whatever it is.

08:59.250 --> 09:04.170
- Having a right
and doing what is right

09:04.190 --> 09:06.290
are two
completely different things.

09:08.230 --> 09:09.780
For what it's worth, Hank,

09:09.800 --> 09:12.730
I'm truly sorry for your loss.

09:24.710 --> 09:28.160
- It's your show,
Mr. Forest.

09:28.180 --> 09:31.400
- [sighs]
- That won't be necessary.

09:31.420 --> 09:33.330
The People will not oppose
Mr. Forest's motion

09:33.350 --> 09:35.370
to suppress the defendant's
confession to the police.

09:35.390 --> 09:37.440
[crowd murmuring]

09:37.460 --> 09:43.240
♪

09:43.260 --> 09:46.310
- It's nice Mr. Stone recognizes
the weaknesses in his case.

09:46.330 --> 09:47.380
Perhaps he'd consider...

09:47.400 --> 09:49.150
- The People intend to proceed
to trial, Your Honor.

09:49.170 --> 09:50.250
- So be it.

09:50.270 --> 09:52.240
[gavel bangs]

09:58.410 --> 09:59.650
- Peter, I found something odd.

10:01.250 --> 10:03.430
It was in with Forest's response
for discovery

10:03.450 --> 10:06.100
and the documents
his office sent over.

10:06.120 --> 10:07.870
- Looks like a list
of Internet articles

10:07.890 --> 10:09.300
about the Kimball Factory.

10:09.320 --> 10:10.770
It was probably sent to us
by mistake.

10:10.790 --> 10:13.510
- A big one. Look closer.
The one that's circled.

10:13.530 --> 10:17.180
- "Kimball Factory:
A Kiddie Sex Den"?

10:17.200 --> 10:19.550
- The article was posted
a few weeks ago

10:19.570 --> 10:21.180
on "The Anders Report."

10:21.200 --> 10:22.880
I printed it out.

10:22.900 --> 10:24.820
The Anders Website claims

10:24.840 --> 10:27.490
the factory was a haven
for pedophiles.

10:27.510 --> 10:30.190
They threw the raves
to attract underage teens.

10:30.210 --> 10:32.730
I spoke to a shrink,

10:32.750 --> 10:35.290
and apparently,
one of the possible consequences

10:35.310 --> 10:37.360
of child abuse is pyromania.

10:37.380 --> 10:42.200
[tense music]

10:42.220 --> 10:44.740
- You wanted a motive.
Now we have one.

10:44.760 --> 10:46.270
- I don't know.

10:46.290 --> 10:47.870
- Dylan Oates was a victim
of sexual abuse.

10:47.890 --> 10:49.740
He read the article,
it brought back memories,

10:49.760 --> 10:50.880
and he lost it.

10:50.900 --> 10:51.840
- [sighs]

10:51.860 --> 10:54.310
This could be considered
attorney work product.

10:54.330 --> 10:56.820
- What do you want me to do?
I can't unsee it.

10:56.840 --> 10:58.220
This is a good thing, Mark.

10:58.240 --> 10:59.920
At least we know
what Forest is thinking.

10:59.940 --> 11:01.520
- You'd be handing Forest
a sympathy defense

11:01.540 --> 11:02.660
on a silver planner with that.

11:02.680 --> 11:05.220
- If he was going to assert
an affirmative defense,

11:05.240 --> 11:06.130
he would have done it already,

11:06.150 --> 11:07.790
and I would get to
cross-examine Dylan

11:07.810 --> 11:09.500
about every second
of that night,

11:09.520 --> 11:12.270
about every innocent person
that died because of him.

11:12.290 --> 11:14.330
The last thing Forest wants
is for the sympathy pendulum

11:14.350 --> 11:15.770
to swing back to me.

11:15.790 --> 11:17.870
- No. No, no, no, no.

11:17.890 --> 11:20.610
We've got 39
grieving families out there.

11:20.630 --> 11:22.540
This case
is too damned important

11:22.560 --> 11:24.240
to risk playing lawyer games.

11:24.260 --> 11:26.810
Now, you've got real facts
on your side.

11:26.830 --> 11:28.570
Use them.

11:32.240 --> 11:34.520
- We found the remains
of the incendiary device

11:34.540 --> 11:36.360
inside the warehouse.

11:36.380 --> 11:38.490
- What kind
of incendiary device?

11:38.510 --> 11:40.790
- It was a lightbulb
filled with gasoline

11:40.810 --> 11:45.230
and a mixture of quartz
and diatomaceous silica.

11:45.250 --> 11:47.530
It's kitty litter.

11:47.550 --> 11:49.270
- Sounds simple.
- It is.

11:49.290 --> 11:50.540
You can learn
everything you need to know

11:50.560 --> 11:52.270
just by going online.

11:52.290 --> 11:53.540
- What else did you find
in the warehouse?

11:53.560 --> 11:54.740
- We found metal wedges

11:54.760 --> 11:57.410
that had been jammed into
the doorways of the warehouse.

11:57.430 --> 11:58.980
- What did that tell you?

11:59.000 --> 12:02.270
- Somebody didn't want
the people inside to get out.

12:06.440 --> 12:08.550
- Tell me about Barry Kimball.

12:08.570 --> 12:11.220
- He was the owner
of the factory that burned.

12:11.240 --> 12:14.860
- Was Mr. Kimball's factory
in violation of the Fire Code?

12:14.880 --> 12:16.600
- There weren't fire doors.

12:16.620 --> 12:18.230
And four years ago,
he was ordered

12:18.250 --> 12:19.900
to retrofit the wiring,

12:19.920 --> 12:22.670
and he ignored the order.

12:22.690 --> 12:25.270
- Did you speak to him
about these violations.

12:25.290 --> 12:27.310
- He came to the Firehouse
the day after the fire.

12:27.330 --> 12:29.440
I wasn't there,
but my crew spoke with him.

12:29.460 --> 12:31.480
- Right after Mr. Kimball
spoke with your crew,

12:31.500 --> 12:33.380
he went into the men's room,
and he shot himself,

12:33.400 --> 12:35.380
isn't that right?

12:35.400 --> 12:36.620
- Yes.

12:36.640 --> 12:37.650
- Is that because
he felt guilty?

12:37.670 --> 12:39.650
- Objection.
- Sustained.

12:39.670 --> 12:41.670
Mr. Forest.

12:47.880 --> 12:51.430
- I-I saw a guy drop a paper bag
on the floor.

12:51.450 --> 12:54.330
- What did he do
after he dropped the paper bag?

12:54.350 --> 12:56.570
- He stepped on it hard,

12:56.590 --> 12:59.000
and... and then he kicked it
under the couch.

12:59.020 --> 13:02.580
And then he just left.
I thought it was weird.

13:02.600 --> 13:05.480
- What's the next thing
you remember?

13:05.500 --> 13:07.710
- I looked to go see
what it was.

13:07.730 --> 13:10.620
And then there was this...
This flash of light.

13:10.640 --> 13:12.490
And then I went down.

13:12.510 --> 13:14.320
- Can you describe him?

13:14.340 --> 13:17.560
- He was 5'8",
blonde, blue eyes.

13:17.580 --> 13:19.530
- Could you describe
what he was wearing?

13:19.550 --> 13:22.500
- He was wearing a...

13:22.520 --> 13:26.990
a brown cargo jacket
with a ForeRange logo on it.

13:30.520 --> 13:32.470
- Was there anything else?
- Yeah, he was...

13:32.490 --> 13:35.740
he was wearing a ring.

13:35.760 --> 13:37.380
- Can you describe the ring?

13:37.400 --> 13:38.480
- It was silver.

13:38.500 --> 13:41.500
It was like
a skull made of silver.

13:42.770 --> 13:44.600
- Thank you.

13:46.970 --> 13:50.710
- Tamra, were you drinking
that night?

13:52.750 --> 13:54.690
- I had...
I had two beers.

13:54.710 --> 13:57.600
- Did you consume any drugs?

13:57.620 --> 14:00.670
[somber music]

14:00.690 --> 14:02.640
♪

14:02.660 --> 14:06.000
You have to answer
the question, Tamra.

14:06.020 --> 14:08.710
- Yes.
- What kind of drugs?

14:08.730 --> 14:11.610
- I had a half tab of Molly.

14:11.630 --> 14:13.710
But I saw what I saw.

14:13.730 --> 14:16.580
- Was there music playing?

14:16.600 --> 14:18.680
- Yes.
- Any kind of light show?

14:18.700 --> 14:20.950
- They had...
They had strobe lights.

14:20.970 --> 14:23.420
- And how long
did you see this person,

14:23.440 --> 14:25.760
the one who stepped
on the paper bag?

14:25.780 --> 14:27.690
- Maybe three seconds.

14:27.710 --> 14:30.560
- So, in a crowded room,
after you'd been drinking

14:30.580 --> 14:33.130
and popping pills
with music pumping

14:33.150 --> 14:36.130
and lights pulsating,
you were really able

14:36.150 --> 14:40.140
to see and identify a ring
on the finger of a stranger?

14:40.160 --> 14:42.110
- [voice breaking] I saw it...

14:42.130 --> 14:44.540
and his face.

14:44.560 --> 14:46.610
I'll never forget it.

14:46.630 --> 14:50.820
- But, unfortunately, you're not
able to identify my client

14:50.840 --> 14:52.720
as the man you saw that night,
are you?

14:52.740 --> 14:55.090
- No, I can't.

14:55.110 --> 14:57.720
I can't see anything
because of him.

14:57.740 --> 14:59.460
[crowd murmuring]

14:59.480 --> 15:01.730
♪

15:01.750 --> 15:04.460
[sobs]

15:04.480 --> 15:07.130
♪

15:07.150 --> 15:10.500
- We found metal wedges
in the defendant's apartment.

15:10.520 --> 15:12.740
- Were they manufactured
by Elliston Industries?

15:12.760 --> 15:16.640
- Yes. Stainless steel.
1 5/8-inch slot width.

15:16.660 --> 15:18.180
- Like this?

15:18.200 --> 15:19.310
- Exactly.

15:19.330 --> 15:21.850
- Can you describe the wedges
shoved under the door

15:21.870 --> 15:24.150
at the factory
where the rave took place?

15:24.170 --> 15:27.650
- Stainless steel,
1 5/8-inch slot width,

15:27.670 --> 15:30.420
manufactured
by Elliston Industries.

15:30.440 --> 15:32.710
- Like this?
- Yes, sir.

15:36.880 --> 15:40.200
- People use these wedges
to hold doors open,

15:40.220 --> 15:41.570
isn't that right?

15:41.590 --> 15:43.640
- Or closed, as the case may be.

15:43.660 --> 15:45.500
- Say you wanted to keep
your terrace door open

15:45.520 --> 15:47.810
so you could enjoy the summer
breeze while you ate dinner,

15:47.830 --> 15:49.480
you'd use one?

15:49.500 --> 15:53.850
- Well, I don't have a terrace,
so I wouldn't know.

15:53.870 --> 15:55.850
- One of the victims
in this case

15:55.870 --> 15:58.520
is the daughter
of one of your colleagues,

15:58.540 --> 16:00.520
isn't that right?
- Alvin Olinsky.

16:00.540 --> 16:02.860
His daughter Lexi was killed
by the fire.

16:02.880 --> 16:06.160
- And getting someone,
anyone, convicted

16:06.180 --> 16:08.690
for what happened
to Detective Olinsky's daughter

16:08.710 --> 16:11.130
would bring him some sort
of closure, wouldn't it?

16:11.150 --> 16:13.700
- Objection.
- Withdrawn.

16:13.720 --> 16:18.770
I show you what is marked
Defense Exhibit 12.

16:18.790 --> 16:21.670
You recognize that?

16:21.690 --> 16:23.540
- It's my arrest report.

16:23.560 --> 16:27.180
- Would you read
the highlighted part?

16:27.200 --> 16:30.180
- "After advising suspect
of his Miranda rights,

16:30.200 --> 16:31.750
"he stated of his own free will,

16:31.770 --> 16:34.840
'It was me, okay?
I started the damn fire.'"

16:36.580 --> 16:38.160
- It's curious, don't you think,

16:38.180 --> 16:41.660
that the People haven't entered
that statement into evidence?

16:41.680 --> 16:43.730
- Objection!
- I'm curious, too, Mr. Stone.

16:43.750 --> 16:45.160
Overruled.

16:45.180 --> 16:48.170
- Why haven't the People entered
Mr. Oates' statement

16:48.190 --> 16:50.670
into evidence, Detective?
- You'd have to ask the People.

16:50.690 --> 16:53.240
- Could it be
that they didn't trust you?

16:53.260 --> 16:55.240
And if the Assistant State's
Attorney doesn't trust you

16:55.260 --> 16:56.840
with something as simple
as a confession,

16:56.860 --> 16:59.570
why should we trust
anything you say now?

17:03.600 --> 17:04.869
Exactly.

17:15.650 --> 17:15.790
.

17:15.810 --> 17:16.819
- In person, Forest is
a lot better than his book.

17:17.420 --> 17:19.260
We read it in law school.

17:19.280 --> 17:21.730
- The Third Edition?
- Thank you.

17:21.750 --> 17:24.160
No, the Fifth.

17:26.829 --> 17:29.110
Could you do it...

17:29.130 --> 17:31.610
defend someone like Dylan Oates?

17:31.630 --> 17:34.080
- I won't ever have to make
that decision.

17:34.100 --> 17:37.120
- So you are a lifer?

17:37.140 --> 17:40.120
- I was thrilled when I was
drafted by the Cubs, Anna...

17:40.140 --> 17:42.860
back when they were
the loveable losers.

17:42.880 --> 17:45.660
An underdog always needs
someone on his side.

17:45.680 --> 17:48.290
- Representing the State doesn't
exactly make you the underdog.

17:48.310 --> 17:49.230
- When I'm in that courtroom,

17:49.250 --> 17:52.160
I'm not thinking
about the State of Illinois.

17:52.180 --> 17:55.790
I'm thinking about the victims.

18:01.360 --> 18:05.180
And right now
I am letting 39 of them down.

18:05.200 --> 18:08.350
Forest is well on his way to
establishing reasonable doubt.

18:08.370 --> 18:10.050
I don't have a choice.

18:10.070 --> 18:12.220
I can't win this
without offering a motive.

18:12.240 --> 18:14.320
- If you put Anders on the stand
to testify

18:14.340 --> 18:17.660
about the raves being used
for underage sex,

18:17.680 --> 18:19.660
Forest will go ballistic.

18:19.680 --> 18:21.280
- Let him.

18:25.380 --> 18:28.370
Ah, Mr. Anders, thank you
for coming in on a Saturday.

18:28.390 --> 18:29.670
This won't take long.

18:29.690 --> 18:31.140
I'm sure you don't need
much prep.

18:31.160 --> 18:34.810
- Uh, I don't think
I'll need any...

18:34.830 --> 18:37.880
mainly 'cause
I'm not gonna testify.

18:37.900 --> 18:39.340
- You have a subpoena
in your hand.

18:39.360 --> 18:42.820
- And the First Amendment
and the shield law at my back.

18:42.840 --> 18:45.220
I'm a journalist, after all.

18:45.240 --> 18:46.790
- I don't know what it is
you do exactly,

18:46.810 --> 18:49.350
but I wouldn't call it
journalism.

18:49.370 --> 18:52.690
- Be that as it may,
I'm not getting on the stand.

18:52.710 --> 18:54.630
- We could have you arrested
for contempt.

18:54.650 --> 18:58.860
- Speaking of which,
I was just thinking recently

18:58.880 --> 19:02.230
of a weekend you spent
at the Huntington Hotel

19:02.250 --> 19:04.200
in Grand Beach.

19:04.220 --> 19:06.240
When was that...

19:06.260 --> 19:07.870
four years ago?

19:07.890 --> 19:10.680
[dramatic music]

19:10.700 --> 19:12.950
- Why are you doing this?

19:12.970 --> 19:14.850
What are you so scared of?

19:14.870 --> 19:17.350
- Do you have any idea
what it would cost me

19:17.370 --> 19:19.890
to defend the lawsuits
brought by the 39 families

19:19.910 --> 19:21.320
who lost their kids?

19:21.340 --> 19:23.360
- They'd have to prove
your story wasn't true.

19:23.380 --> 19:25.160
- Then I'd be forced
to name my sources.

19:25.180 --> 19:29.830
♪

19:29.850 --> 19:32.130
Give my best to Joan.

19:32.150 --> 19:39.190
♪

19:52.940 --> 19:55.950
- Damn it, Peter.
We had a deal.

19:55.970 --> 19:58.960
No calls, no texts,
and definitely no lunches.

19:58.980 --> 20:01.850
- Like I said,
this is important.

20:04.450 --> 20:08.400
- [clears throat]

20:08.420 --> 20:10.440
How bad is it?

20:10.460 --> 20:11.970
- Have you heard of Todd Anders?

20:11.990 --> 20:14.760
- The sleazy-Website guy?
- Yeah.

20:16.800 --> 20:18.340
He threatened to publish
something about our weekend

20:18.360 --> 20:20.800
at Grand Beach
if I put him on the stand.

20:23.300 --> 20:25.350
- Well, then don't put him
on the stand.

20:25.370 --> 20:27.450
- This is
on the rave trial, Joan.

20:27.470 --> 20:29.820
His testimony will help me
establish motive.

20:29.840 --> 20:32.020
- I said no.

20:32.040 --> 20:34.460
- 39 kids died.
- And I'm married.

20:34.480 --> 20:37.960
- You were separated
at the time.

20:37.980 --> 20:42.220
- I doubt that Sam or the girls
will split those hairs.

20:43.220 --> 20:45.770
♪

20:45.790 --> 20:48.340
You're not asking
my permission, are you?

20:48.360 --> 20:52.040
♪

20:52.060 --> 20:53.910
- I'm sorry.

20:53.930 --> 20:56.010
♪

20:56.030 --> 20:57.280
- No, you're not.

20:57.300 --> 20:58.820
You only care
about your damn case.

20:58.840 --> 20:59.820
- Joan, please.

20:59.840 --> 21:01.490
- You're gonna
ruin my life, Peter.

21:01.510 --> 21:04.790
Pardon me if I don't want
to break bread with you.

21:04.810 --> 21:09.060
♪

21:09.080 --> 21:11.060
- [sighs]

21:11.080 --> 21:18.260
♪

21:21.090 --> 21:22.840
- Mr. Anders...

21:22.860 --> 21:24.780
I direct your attention
to what is being offered

21:24.800 --> 21:26.800
as People's Exhibit 53.

21:28.870 --> 21:32.380
Do you recognize this document,
Mr. Anders?

21:32.400 --> 21:34.850
- It is an article
that was published

21:34.870 --> 21:37.260
on my Website.

21:37.280 --> 21:38.520
- Please read the headline.

21:38.540 --> 21:41.330
- "Kimball Factory:
A Kiddie Sex Den."

21:41.350 --> 21:43.960
- And the essence
of the story is what?

21:43.980 --> 21:47.970
- That people threw parties
at the abandoned factory

21:47.990 --> 21:50.900
to lure underage teens
to engage in sexual acts.

21:50.920 --> 21:52.870
- They'd get them
drunk and high?

21:52.890 --> 21:53.870
- That's right.

21:53.890 --> 21:55.340
- If someone read this,

21:55.360 --> 21:57.580
might they do
something drastic about it?

21:57.600 --> 22:01.000
- I'm not gonna answer that.
- Nor should you have to.

22:02.970 --> 22:04.770
- I have nothing more,
Your Honor.

22:07.070 --> 22:10.360
- Mr. Forest?
- Uh, no questions.

22:10.380 --> 22:11.960
No questions, Your Honor.

22:11.980 --> 22:13.390
- Mr. Stone?

22:13.410 --> 22:16.330
♪

22:16.350 --> 22:17.560
- The People rest.

22:17.580 --> 22:20.390
- Fine, gentlemen. The defense
can present in the morning.

22:31.860 --> 22:32.860
- Are you okay?

22:33.870 --> 22:36.870
- [sighs] I've been better.

22:38.140 --> 22:40.220
Forest didn't object
to the document

22:40.240 --> 22:42.860
or my question to Anders.

22:42.880 --> 22:45.160
He didn't cross Anders
about his sources.

22:45.180 --> 22:46.960
Why?

22:46.980 --> 22:49.210
- Maybe Anders has
something on him.

22:55.220 --> 22:58.000
[sighs] It's a little late
for Forest's book.

22:58.020 --> 22:59.960
- Read the title
of chapter three.

23:01.330 --> 23:04.110
- "Trials: It's All A Con."

23:04.130 --> 23:06.160
- And I think I'm his mark.

23:12.100 --> 23:15.910
- I never thought Dylan could do
something like this.

23:17.310 --> 23:18.390
[exhales deeply]

23:18.410 --> 23:20.290
- But you do now?

23:20.310 --> 23:23.260
- No. Of course not.

23:23.280 --> 23:26.030
He was always such a sweet boy.

23:26.050 --> 23:28.170
That's what I called him...
My sweet boy.

23:28.190 --> 23:30.300
[voice breaking]
I know it's silly.

23:30.320 --> 23:35.110
- Was there a time
when he stopped being sweet?

23:35.130 --> 23:37.940
- Dylan was five.

23:37.960 --> 23:40.050
My brother Frank
was taking him fishing.

23:40.070 --> 23:43.000
He was so excited, you know,
like little boys get.

23:45.140 --> 23:48.620
When he got home,
he was different.

23:48.640 --> 23:51.060
- You're lying.
- Watch it, young man.

23:51.080 --> 23:54.090
- I know what he did to you.

23:54.110 --> 23:57.400
From the time he was five
until Frank died.

23:57.420 --> 23:59.330
- She's lying!
She knows nothing about me!

23:59.350 --> 24:03.100
- Mr. Oates, one more outburst,
and I will have you removed.

24:03.120 --> 24:05.970
♪

24:05.990 --> 24:07.940
- Did Dylan say anything
about it to you?

24:07.960 --> 24:09.040
- No.

24:09.060 --> 24:11.980
- Then how can you be so sure
it happened, Mrs. Oates?

24:12.000 --> 24:14.280
- I'm his mother.

24:14.300 --> 24:16.980
- Are you aware
that you just confessed

24:17.000 --> 24:20.050
to endangering
the welfare of a child?

24:20.070 --> 24:22.420
- That fire...

24:22.440 --> 24:25.420
all those kids...

24:25.440 --> 24:29.460
[sniffles] If Dylan did it,
it is my fault,

24:29.480 --> 24:32.000
not his.

24:32.020 --> 24:33.430
[dramatic music]

24:33.450 --> 24:36.000
- Let's break for lunch,
shall we?

24:36.020 --> 24:38.000
[gavel bangs]

24:38.020 --> 24:44.980
♪

24:45.000 --> 24:47.110
[indistinct chatter]

24:47.130 --> 24:50.120
[light jazz playing
over speakers]

24:50.140 --> 24:52.720
♪

24:52.740 --> 24:55.150
- [sighs]

24:55.170 --> 24:58.460
- I assume
this isn't a coincidence.

24:58.480 --> 25:00.990
- It's all a con.

25:01.010 --> 25:03.400
- [chuckles]

25:03.420 --> 25:06.000
Well, at least somebody
pays attention to what I write.

25:06.020 --> 25:06.930
[chuckles]

25:06.950 --> 25:10.700
- "In the courtroom,
reality is irrelevant.

25:10.720 --> 25:12.700
The appearance of reality
is all that matters."

25:12.720 --> 25:15.670
- I do have a way with words.

25:15.690 --> 25:17.210
- That wasn't a mistake...

25:17.230 --> 25:20.110
You sending me
that list of articles.

25:20.130 --> 25:22.180
- Why would I do that
intentionally?

25:22.200 --> 25:24.780
- So I would introduce
your defense for you.

25:24.800 --> 25:27.020
And you'd never have to put
your client on the stand

25:27.040 --> 25:28.790
to be cross-examined.

25:28.810 --> 25:31.220
- Wow. That... that would be
very clever.

25:31.240 --> 25:33.690
- And dishonest.

25:33.710 --> 25:35.430
- Or the appearance thereof.

25:35.450 --> 25:38.030
♪

25:38.050 --> 25:40.270
- Was Dylan really abused?

25:40.290 --> 25:42.330
- His mother
certainly thinks so.

25:42.350 --> 25:45.100
- No. I read the transcript
of her testimony.

25:45.120 --> 25:46.040
She never actually said it.

25:46.060 --> 25:48.040
So you never actually
suborned perjury.

25:48.060 --> 25:49.770
- Jeez, I'm getting smarter
by the minute.

25:49.790 --> 25:51.340
- Is the Anders story true?

25:51.360 --> 25:52.340
- I have no idea.

25:52.360 --> 25:54.310
For me,
it was merely fortuitous.

25:54.330 --> 25:56.550
- This isn't a game.
39 kids are dead.

25:56.570 --> 26:00.190
- And my concern is the one
who's still living.

26:00.210 --> 26:02.320
[dramatic music]

26:02.340 --> 26:06.120
You got a little of your dad
in you, you know that?

26:06.140 --> 26:07.060
You think a criminal trial

26:07.080 --> 26:10.230
is all about some sort
of ineffable morality,

26:10.250 --> 26:15.300
something out there
that's permanent and infinite.

26:15.320 --> 26:19.100
I got news for you, son...
There ain't no such thing.

26:19.120 --> 26:22.140
What happens in that courtroom
is a zero-sum game.

26:22.160 --> 26:24.840
There's winners
and losers, period.

26:24.860 --> 26:28.080
- So why concern yourself
with using a fake news story

26:28.100 --> 26:30.220
as long as it puts
a W in your column?

26:30.240 --> 26:33.150
- Or at least an M
for "mistrial."

26:33.170 --> 26:34.820
♪

26:34.840 --> 26:38.820
Odds are, out of the 12 ordinary
citizens in the jury box,

26:38.840 --> 26:41.260
child sexual abuse will hit home
for one of them.

26:41.280 --> 26:45.500
And that, my friend,
spells hung jury.

26:45.520 --> 26:46.830
- I'll retry him.

26:46.850 --> 26:49.300
- And I'll find
another reality...

26:49.320 --> 26:52.370
maybe even one that's
more acceptable to my client.

26:52.390 --> 26:59.500
♪

27:04.400 --> 27:06.100
[door opens]

27:09.810 --> 27:13.360
[door closes]

27:13.380 --> 27:15.810
- The People have no questions
for Mrs. Oates.

27:19.480 --> 27:23.240
- You may go.
Thank you.

27:23.260 --> 27:26.370
- In that case,
the defense rests, Your Honor.

27:26.390 --> 27:29.810
- I think counsel
is jumping the gun.

27:29.830 --> 27:32.810
The People certainly have
the right to examine Mr. Oates.

27:32.830 --> 27:34.850
- [chuckles]

27:34.870 --> 27:36.450
This is still America.

27:36.470 --> 27:39.220
We still have a constitution
and a Fifth Amendment...

27:39.240 --> 27:41.490
- Your Honor, let me remind you
how the defendant reacted

27:41.510 --> 27:44.590
when his mother
was on the stand.

27:44.610 --> 27:46.560
- Your Honor, may we approach?

27:46.580 --> 27:48.880
- Yes. Come.

27:53.450 --> 27:55.200
- Your Honor,
my client was upset.

27:55.220 --> 27:58.300
- He spoke. The jury heard him.
That's testimony.

27:58.320 --> 28:00.470
He waived his rights
against self-incrimination.

28:00.490 --> 28:03.340
- Oh, please. Your Honor...
- Clever, Mr. Stone...

28:03.360 --> 28:05.510
very clever.

28:05.530 --> 28:08.910
I'll probably be reversed
on appeal,

28:08.930 --> 28:10.850
but I'm gonna let you
cross-examine him,

28:10.870 --> 28:14.470
but only as to the matters
that he testified to on direct.

28:15.670 --> 28:18.190
I assume you're gonna need time

28:18.210 --> 28:19.620
to prepare your client,
Mr. Forest.

28:19.640 --> 28:21.450
I'll give you 24 hours.

28:25.720 --> 28:29.400
- All you can cross Dylan on
is whether his mom was lying

28:29.420 --> 28:31.270
or whether she actually
knew anything about his life.

28:31.290 --> 28:33.570
- So we need to find out
something she didn't know.

28:33.590 --> 28:35.410
Somebody at the rave
must have known him.

28:35.430 --> 28:37.410
- CPD spoke to everybody
who came forward.

28:37.430 --> 28:38.440
[both sigh]

28:38.460 --> 28:41.310
- Have Dawson and Nagel
find someone who didn't.

28:41.330 --> 28:44.370
[train rattling loudly]

28:56.750 --> 28:58.430
- Hey.

28:58.450 --> 29:00.900
- Hey.

29:00.920 --> 29:04.670
Did you tell Stone
about the confession?

29:04.690 --> 29:06.900
- I didn't have to.

29:06.920 --> 29:08.640
- You know, I should have
whacked that little bastard

29:08.660 --> 29:11.400
when I had the chance.

29:14.530 --> 29:16.380
- Hey, Dawson.

29:16.400 --> 29:18.520
Look what I found on this teddy.

29:18.540 --> 29:21.290
"Dear Arnie, I'm so sorry.
It's all my fault.

29:21.310 --> 29:22.920
Love always, Chloe."

29:22.940 --> 29:25.260
There's no Chloe
on the survivors list.

29:25.280 --> 29:26.620
- Who's Arnie?

29:26.640 --> 29:28.560
- There was an Arnold Phillips.

29:28.580 --> 29:31.330
He died in the fire.

29:31.350 --> 29:33.320
- Okay.

29:36.690 --> 29:40.540
[music playing faintly
over headphones]

29:40.560 --> 29:42.670
- Hey, Chloe.

29:42.690 --> 29:45.010
- Who are you?
- I'm Laura.

29:45.030 --> 29:46.540
I'm investigating the fire.

29:46.560 --> 29:48.510
Um, your mom said
I could come up.

29:48.530 --> 29:49.780
She's talking to my partner.

29:49.800 --> 29:51.550
[music stops]

29:51.570 --> 29:52.780
It's important, Chloe.

29:52.800 --> 29:55.290
This could help us convict
the guy responsible.

29:55.310 --> 29:57.780
- I wasn't there.
I don't know anything.

30:04.520 --> 30:07.000
- I have a daughter.
She's eight.

30:07.020 --> 30:09.300
And I know in a few years,
she's gonna start

30:09.320 --> 30:11.300
keeping secrets from me.

30:11.320 --> 30:13.290
- Can you leave me alone?

30:24.670 --> 30:26.720
[cries]

30:26.740 --> 30:30.020
- I know you were there.

30:30.040 --> 30:34.090
And I know how difficult
it must be to lose a brother.

30:34.110 --> 30:36.660
- [sniffles]

30:36.680 --> 30:40.000
[dramatic music]

30:40.020 --> 30:42.730
Arnie didn't want to go.

30:42.750 --> 30:45.400
I was a jerk.
I kept begging him.

30:45.420 --> 30:49.360
And then when I saw the guy
they arrested on the news...

30:50.500 --> 30:53.680
I didn't know what to do.

30:53.700 --> 30:55.680
- You recognized him?

30:55.700 --> 30:58.050
♪

30:58.070 --> 31:00.020
- Yeah.

31:00.040 --> 31:02.650
When I went outside
to have a cigarette,

31:02.670 --> 31:04.690
he was out there...

31:04.710 --> 31:07.360
pacing back and forth.

31:07.380 --> 31:10.720
And then when I went in,
he was arguing with some girl.

31:12.580 --> 31:15.370
- I want... I want you to tell me
if you recognize her.

31:15.390 --> 31:20.770
♪

31:20.790 --> 31:22.490
- No.

31:24.400 --> 31:27.610
Yeah. That's her.

31:27.630 --> 31:29.100
Yeah.

31:30.640 --> 31:32.880
- Thank you.

31:32.900 --> 31:35.150
- I don't know a Dylan Oates.

31:35.170 --> 31:37.460
- He seems to know you.

31:37.480 --> 31:40.390
Our tech people found that Dylan
had a Facebook account

31:40.410 --> 31:42.530
under the fake name Kurt Holden.

31:42.550 --> 31:45.060
- I have over a thousand
"friends."

31:45.080 --> 31:46.030
I don't know all of them.

31:46.050 --> 31:50.640
- Dylan only friended
one person, Tamra... you.

31:50.660 --> 31:53.910
- We know you saw him do more
than just step on the paper bag.

31:53.930 --> 31:58.580
[teacup rattling on plate]

31:58.600 --> 32:00.410
- Oh, God.

32:00.430 --> 32:04.440
[sighing]

32:09.570 --> 32:13.460
He came up to me at the rave.

32:13.480 --> 32:14.630
He said that he knew me,

32:14.650 --> 32:17.700
that we'd met on the L,
like, three months ago, but...

32:17.720 --> 32:21.170
I had no idea.

32:21.190 --> 32:25.540
He said that he asked me to have
a cup of coffee back then.

32:25.560 --> 32:27.470
- Did you go out with him?
- No.

32:27.490 --> 32:29.470
I-I had to study.

32:29.490 --> 32:31.880
That's what he said I told him.

32:31.900 --> 32:34.610
But I swear,
I don't remember this at all.

32:34.630 --> 32:38.520
- What else
did he tell you, Tamra?

32:38.540 --> 32:42.450
- He said that I went to a party
instead of going out with him.

32:42.470 --> 32:45.120
But how could he possibly
know that?

32:45.140 --> 32:47.590
- You posted it on Facebook.

32:47.610 --> 32:54.620
♪

32:56.150 --> 32:58.660
- [voice breaking] Oh, God...

33:03.930 --> 33:08.180
[sobbing] All those people are
dead because of me, aren't they?

33:08.200 --> 33:15.190
♪

33:15.210 --> 33:17.490
- [sobs]

33:17.510 --> 33:19.690
- I'm sorry, Tamra,
but you'll have to testify...

33:19.710 --> 33:21.860
- Only if we need you.

33:21.880 --> 33:26.480
♪

33:35.390 --> 33:36.870
- Why did you call your mother
a liar?

33:39.200 --> 33:42.180
- That story about my uncle...

33:42.200 --> 33:43.720
It's a total lie.

33:43.740 --> 33:46.050
He never
did anything weird to me.

33:46.070 --> 33:48.190
- So why would your mom say it
under oath?

33:48.210 --> 33:50.580
- 'Cause she's stupid.

33:52.680 --> 33:54.530
- Did you think
boys were being molested

33:54.550 --> 33:55.930
at the Kimball Warehouse?
- Objection.

33:55.950 --> 33:57.190
Beyond the scope.
- Sustained.

33:57.210 --> 33:59.960
- Did you ever read an article
about it in "The Anders Report"?

33:59.980 --> 34:01.630
- Same objection.
- Sustained.

34:01.650 --> 34:03.670
Mr. Stone,
you're limited to questions

34:03.690 --> 34:06.590
relating to the defendant's
prior outburst.

34:10.699 --> 34:13.650
- Tell me, Dylan...
Why did you say that

34:13.670 --> 34:16.080
your mom doesn't know anything
about your life?

34:16.100 --> 34:17.679
- Because she doesn't.

34:17.699 --> 34:19.580
- Did she know
you were on Facebook?

34:19.600 --> 34:23.050
- [laughs]
I'm not. I mean, it's lame.

34:23.070 --> 34:24.659
- So why did you start
an account

34:24.679 --> 34:27.080
under the fake name
"Kurt Holden"?

34:30.010 --> 34:31.960
- I have no idea
what you're talking about.

34:31.980 --> 34:33.199
- Did your mom know
you were obsessed

34:33.219 --> 34:35.120
with a girl on social media?

34:37.020 --> 34:39.219
- Even if I were,
I wouldn't tell her.

34:41.989 --> 34:44.739
- Do you know who this girl is?

34:44.760 --> 34:46.130
- No.

34:47.159 --> 34:49.580
- How about this one?

34:49.600 --> 34:51.639
- No.

34:55.670 --> 34:57.610
- Who is that, Dylan?

35:02.710 --> 35:06.250
- She's the blind one
who said she knows me.

35:07.720 --> 35:09.800
- Her name is Tamra Collins.

35:09.820 --> 35:14.030
And her face was all over the
newsfeed on your phony account.

35:16.290 --> 35:18.730
These were photos
that you liked.

35:21.200 --> 35:24.180
[dramatic music]

35:24.200 --> 35:31.240
♪

35:34.880 --> 35:36.830
Hmm.

35:36.850 --> 35:38.800
Looks like she's having
a great time.

35:38.820 --> 35:45.800
♪

35:45.820 --> 35:48.770
- Whatever.

35:48.790 --> 35:50.310
- Did this make you
a little jealous?

35:50.330 --> 35:53.380
- Objection.
- Withdrawn.

35:53.400 --> 35:57.050
Did your mom know that you asked
Tamra out three months ago?

35:57.070 --> 35:58.880
- No. Because I didn't.

35:58.900 --> 36:01.120
- Did she know that
Tamra made up some lame excuse

36:01.140 --> 36:03.050
to dump you
while she went to a rave?

36:03.070 --> 36:05.420
- No.
Because that never happened.

36:05.440 --> 36:09.190
- Did you ever tell your mom
how humiliated you felt?

36:09.210 --> 36:10.800
♪

36:10.820 --> 36:12.800
- Why would I care
if some bimbo preferred

36:12.820 --> 36:14.670
to be with garbage
instead of me?

36:14.690 --> 36:16.730
- So you'd just as soon
sit at home alone

36:16.750 --> 36:20.100
on your computer?

36:20.120 --> 36:21.910
- As a matter of fact, I would.

36:21.930 --> 36:23.810
- To hell with Tamra
and her friends, right?

36:23.830 --> 36:28.210
- That's right.
They're all irrelevant to me.

36:28.230 --> 36:31.220
- So it's no big deal
that they're all dead?

36:31.240 --> 36:33.820
- Objection.
- Withdrawn.

36:33.840 --> 36:38.120
♪

36:38.140 --> 36:41.360
I have nothing further,
Your Honor.

36:41.380 --> 36:48.390
♪

36:59.360 --> 37:01.270
- Why did he do it?

37:02.430 --> 37:04.350
I don't know either.

37:04.370 --> 37:07.250
Mr. Stone told you
a hell of story

37:07.270 --> 37:10.420
about lightbulbs
and kitty litter,

37:10.440 --> 37:13.220
door wedges,
brown cargo jackets,

37:13.240 --> 37:16.430
but unless I missed it,
he never quite told you

37:16.450 --> 37:19.160
why Dylan Oates started a fire

37:19.180 --> 37:23.740
at a party filled with people
he didn't know.

37:23.760 --> 37:26.170
But the truth...

37:26.190 --> 37:28.910
is that lots of people
have lightbulbs

37:28.930 --> 37:32.980
and kitty litter, door wedges,
brown cargo jackets.

37:33.000 --> 37:36.780
But only one had the motive...

37:36.800 --> 37:40.750
to cause
such unutterable devastation.

37:40.770 --> 37:42.350
Now, was it Dylan Oates?

37:42.370 --> 37:45.960
Or did Mr. Stone merely
pull a patsy out of a hat?

37:45.980 --> 37:49.390
A patsy who happened to have
a brown cargo jacket?

37:49.410 --> 37:53.830
A patsy whose childhood
was tormented

37:53.850 --> 37:57.970
by such unspeakable
indignities...

37:57.990 --> 38:00.170
he would risk going to prison

38:00.190 --> 38:03.910
rather than admit
what really happened?

38:03.930 --> 38:05.380
No.

38:05.400 --> 38:08.880
If it was Dylan Oates
who started the fire,

38:08.900 --> 38:10.450
surely Mr. Stone
would have answered

38:10.470 --> 38:13.000
that one simple,
crucial question...

38:15.240 --> 38:16.810
Why?

38:32.460 --> 38:34.330
- 39 children dead.

38:36.360 --> 38:37.410
Mr. Forest is correct.

38:37.430 --> 38:40.910
I didn't tell you
why Dylan Oates set that fire

38:40.930 --> 38:44.040
and killed these 39 innocents.

38:45.370 --> 38:47.280
I didn't have to...

38:47.300 --> 38:50.590
because Dylan told you himself.

38:50.610 --> 38:52.060
He said it here.

38:52.080 --> 38:54.050
And here...

38:57.480 --> 39:00.020
And here.

39:06.020 --> 39:08.840
He said it the way people say
most things today...

39:08.860 --> 39:13.580
Digitally, by text or Twitter
or Tumblr or Facebook.

39:13.600 --> 39:16.480
He told you he was obsessed
with Tamra Collins,

39:16.500 --> 39:17.980
a woman he met only briefly

39:18.000 --> 39:20.520
but still wanted
nothing to do with him.

39:20.540 --> 39:22.290
He stalked her,

39:22.310 --> 39:24.290
not by following her home
or to work,

39:24.310 --> 39:25.560
but on social media.

39:25.580 --> 39:28.530
Why?
Because that's the world...

39:28.550 --> 39:31.260
Dylan Oates inhabits.

39:31.280 --> 39:34.000
The rectangular-bordered
landscape of his desktop,

39:34.020 --> 39:36.570
laptop, iPad, smartphone.
[hand tapping]

39:36.590 --> 39:38.870
A world where someone,
with a couple of keystrokes,

39:38.890 --> 39:43.010
can express anger, love, hate

39:43.030 --> 39:47.610
to anyone anywhere
without risk of reprisal.

39:47.630 --> 39:51.120
It's a world
where deceit flourishes

39:51.140 --> 39:54.490
and voyeurism thrives...
[tapping continues]

39:54.510 --> 39:58.460
Where real human contact
and discourse

39:58.480 --> 40:02.390
is replaced by bits and bytes
and logarithms.

40:02.410 --> 40:04.400
Where Tamra Collins
is always smiling...

40:04.420 --> 40:06.060
[hand pounding]
- Dylan.

40:06.080 --> 40:09.600
- Always at a party,
and always having a great time.

40:09.620 --> 40:11.070
[pounding on table]

40:11.090 --> 40:12.500
- Dylan.
- Mr. Oates, that's enough!

40:12.520 --> 40:14.310
- Dylan.

40:14.330 --> 40:16.440
You got to control yourself.

40:16.460 --> 40:23.470
♪

40:24.470 --> 40:27.920
- See, in Dylan's head,
Tamra had...

40:27.940 --> 40:30.050
a perfect life.

40:30.070 --> 40:32.460
♪

40:32.480 --> 40:33.930
And Dylan wasn't invited.

40:33.950 --> 40:37.930
♪

40:37.950 --> 40:42.330
How dare she exclude you
from her perfect world?

40:42.350 --> 40:44.670
How dare she embarrass you
by announcing to the world

40:44.690 --> 40:48.070
on Facebook
that you weren't part of it?

40:48.090 --> 40:50.110
♪

40:50.130 --> 40:52.440
See, Dylan couldn't let her
get away with that,

40:52.460 --> 40:56.570
so he set fire to the world
that didn't want him.

40:58.100 --> 41:00.370
And then he watched it burn.

41:02.170 --> 41:06.720
Now, I wonder, are those tears
for the 39 dead?

41:06.740 --> 41:10.150
Or are they for your own
sad and lonely life?

41:11.520 --> 41:13.100
- [shouts]
- Officers!

41:13.120 --> 41:15.100
- Dylan!
- Restrain him.

41:15.120 --> 41:16.570
[gavel bangs]

41:16.590 --> 41:18.040
Order in this court.

41:18.060 --> 41:19.570
Mr. Oates.
[gavel bangs]

41:19.590 --> 41:21.640
Mr. Oates, that's enough.

41:21.660 --> 41:24.180
Officers, remove him
from this courtroom.

41:24.200 --> 41:31.400
♪

41:34.010 --> 41:37.050
- "In the matter of
the People versus Dylan Oates,

41:37.070 --> 41:39.560
"on the first count,
aggravated arson,

41:39.580 --> 41:42.990
"the jury finds
the defendant guilty.

41:43.010 --> 41:44.660
"On the second count,

41:44.680 --> 41:48.630
"first-degree murder
of Isabel Acuna, guilty.

41:48.650 --> 41:50.200
"On the third count,

41:50.220 --> 41:54.410
"first-degree murder
of Dana Altamore, guilty.

41:54.430 --> 41:56.110
"On the fourth count,

41:56.130 --> 42:00.140
"first-degree murder
of Lexi Olinksy, guilty.

42:00.160 --> 42:02.050
"On the fifth count,

42:02.070 --> 42:07.050
"first-degree murder
of Alexis Atkinson, guilty.

42:07.070 --> 42:08.550
"On the sixth count,

42:08.570 --> 42:12.710
first-degree murder
of Sam Aliro, guilty"...

42:47.210 --> 42:50.210
[wolf howls]
